1. CSV file parliament2015.csv contains the number of votes in the Catalan parliament elections of 2015 by municipalities. Load the dataset.

  • Cluster municipalities according to the proportions of votes to each party. Describe the characteristics of each cluster.
  • Fit a self-organizing map to the data. Tune parameters \(r\) and \(\alpha\) to obtain a good fit.

2. Files Kmeans_class.R and Kmeans_class.py contain an incomplete \(K\)-means class implementation for R and Python. Complete the definition for two main steps, assigment_step() and updating_step(), of the algorithm. The available class has different methods:

  • Initialization function. It receives training data and the number of clusters.
  • set_center(). It receives the initial centroids.
  • assignment_step() (not implemented). Should assign each example to its closest cluster.
  • updating_step() (not implemented). Should update the centroids according to the current assignment.
  • sequential_step() (not implemented). Should update the closest centroids to a given example.
  • plot(). It plots the current assignment, showing only the two first principal components of data.

They should allow you to execute the \(K\)-means algorithm step-by-step:

R

source('kmeans_class.R')

X = iris[,1:4]

set.seed(1)
K = 3
km = Kmeans$new(X, K = K)

S0 = X[1:3,]

km$set_centers(S0)
km$assignment_step()$plot("1st assignment")
km$updating_step()$assignment_step()$plot("2nd assignment")

Python

import numpy as np

exec(open('kmeans_class.py').read())

X = datasets.load_iris().data
np.random.seed(1)
K = 3
km = Kmeans(X, K)

S0 = X[(0,1,2),:]

km = km.set_centers(S0)
km = km.assignment_step()
km.plot("1st assignment")
km = km.updating_step().assignment_step()
km.plot("2nd assignment")

3. A useful algorithm to calculate the mean \(\bar{\textbf{x}}_n\) for the first \(n\) elements of a set of examples \(\textbf{x}_1, \dots, \textbf{x}_N\) is given by [ {}_n = \left{

\[\begin{array}[ll]\\ \textbf{x}_1&\text{if } n=1\\ \bar{\textbf{x}}_{n-1} + \frac{1}{n}(\textbf{x}_n - \bar{\textbf{x}}_{n-1})&\text{if } n>1 \end{array}\]

. ]

  • Implement function sequential_step(x, alpha) to update the closest centroids to a given example \(\textbf{x}\) passing learning rate, \(\alpha\), as parameter. With the implemented function, we can calculate the mean of a sample as

R

mean_ = Kmeans$new(X, K = 1)
mean_$set_centers(X[1,])
for(i in 1:nrow(X)){
  x = X[i,]
  mean_$sequential_step(x, 1/i)
}
mean_$plot()

Python

mean_ = Kmeans(X, K = 1)
mean_.set_centers(np.array([X[0,:]]))
for i in range(X.shape[0]):
  x = X[i,:]
  mean_ = mean_.sequential_step(x, 1/(i+1))

mean_.plot()
## <__main__.Kmeans object at 0x1216f8350>

  • See that the position of the centroid is the same as the average of sample X.
